## Database Optimization — Done ✅

**Table:** `orders` (500M rows)

### What was there before
Only the primary key index on `id`. Every query filtering by user, status, or date was doing a full sequential scan across half a billion rows.

### What was added

| Index | Column | Helps with |
|---|---|---|
| `idx_orders_user_id` | `user_id` | "My orders" lookups — the most common user-facing query |
| `idx_orders_status` | `status` | Filtering by order state (pending/shipped/etc.) — ops dashboards |
| `idx_orders_order_date` | `order_date` | Date-range queries — reporting, analytics |

### How it was done safely
All three indexes were created with `CREATE INDEX CONCURRENTLY` — this only acquires a `ShareUpdateExclusiveLock` (non-blocking), so writes (INSERT/UPDATE/DELETE) continued uninterrupted throughout. No transactions were used, as required. Post-creation lock check confirmed no conflicts.

### Expected impact
Queries filtering or sorting by `user_id`, `status`, or `order_date` should go from full table scans to fast index seeks — typically orders of magnitude faster on a 500M-row table. If you have specific slow queries you'd like me to `EXPLAIN ANALYZE`, I can dig deeper into any remaining bottlenecks.
